                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d860">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War/8–344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-03T21:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 3, 1944—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 3—7:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6209. Immediately on receipt of your 6032 of July 31, I contacted Mr. Pell and
                    also brought the matter to Mr. Eden’s attention, as I found that in spite of Mr.
                    Pell’s protest and dissent, the War Crimes Commission still planned to hold its
                    press conference this morning. It was only with Mr. Eden’s intervention that it
                    was cancelled.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
